    },
    {
      "point": "Rigorously Identifies and Operationalizes Composition Bias",
      "evidence": "Demonstration that model scaling behavior is acutely influenced by the 'composition bias' of train/test sets, specifically the deviation from naturally generated text. Natural text on the target side benefits from scaling, while source-original test sets show saturation."
    },
    {
      "point": "Demonstrates Breakdown of Loss-BLEU Correlation",
      "evidence": "For Source-Original Test Sets: While cross-entropy loss improved with scaling, BLEU scores stopped improving and began to deteriorate after a certain model size threshold. This breakdown in correlation was also observed with BLEURT."
    },
    {
      "point": "Observation of Differential Scaling Exponents",
      "evidence": "The fitted decoder exponents ($p_d$) were consistently larger than encoder exponents ($p_e$) across all test sets ($p_d > p_e$). This suggests scaling the decoder is more effective for reducing cross-entropy loss."
    },
